Nats=====False=====81
During this event, William the Pig and Hugh the Iron offered free transport, but took their unwitting
passengers to Tunisia. A leader of this event is apocryphally said to have performed miracles at the
Cathedral Saint-Denis [sahn deh-NEE]. One leader of this campaign, Stephen of Cloyes [kloy], said he had
a letter from Jesus to the King of France. Nicholas of Cologne’s prediction that the sea by Genoa would
part for this campaign obviously did not come true, and when this crusade ended, most of its participants
were sold into slavery. For the point, name this 1212 crusade named for its youthful participants.=====
Children’s Crusade =====